## Overview: The Seven Books

The series comprises seven volumes. Lewis suggested reading them in the internal chronological order of Narnia's history, though they were published in a different order:

| Publication Order | Title | Narnia Chronological Order |
|---|---|---|
| 1 | *The Lion, the Witch and the Wardrobe* (1950) | 2 |
| 2 | *Prince Caspian* (1951) | 4 |
| 3 | *The Voyage of the Dawn Treader* (1952) | 5 |
| 4 | *The Silver Chair* (1953) | 6 |
| 5 | *The Horse and His Boy* (1954) | 3 |
| 6 | *The Magician's Nephew* (1955) | 1 |
| 7 | *The Last Battle* (1956) | 7 |

## The Lion, the Witch and the Wardrobe

The best-known and most beloved of the series, *The Lion, the Witch and the Wardrobe* introduces the Pevensie children — Peter, Susan, Edmund, and Lucy — who discover through a magical wardrobe a world called **Narnia** in the grip of an eternal winter imposed by the **White Witch**, who has proclaimed "always winter and never Christmas."

The great Lion **Aslan** — creator and true king of Narnia — returns, and the children join in the battle to free the land. When Edmund betrays his siblings to the Witch and she claims his life by the rules of the Deep Magic, Aslan willingly gives his own life in Edmund's place at the **Stone Table**. He rises again, explaining that the Witch knew the Deep Magic (the moral law of Narnia) but not the Deeper Magic — the law that a willing, innocent victim's death in a traitor's place would reverse the Table itself and defeat death.

:::quote C.S. Lewis, *The Lion, the Witch and the Wardrobe*
"It means," said Aslan, "that though the Witch knew the Deep Magic, there is a magic deeper still which she did not know. Her knowledge goes back only to the dawn of Time. But if she could have looked a little further back, into the stillness and the darkness before Time dawned, she would have read there a different incantation."
:::

The parallel to Christ's death and resurrection is unmistakable and deliberate. Lewis designed it so that children who later learned the Gospel story would recognize it as something they had already encountered in Narnia — and find it more credible and moving for that encounter.

## Aslan: The Figure of Christ

**Aslan** is the theological center of the Chronicles. He is explicitly described as the son of the Emperor-over-the-Sea (a figure for God the Father), the creator of Narnia, and its redeemer. He is not a tame lion — he is wild, powerful, terrible, and good — but he is utterly trustworthy and ultimately merciful.

Lewis described his intention in a letter: imagining what it might be like if the Son of God were to take on the nature of a lion in a world of talking animals, much as He took on human nature in our world. Aslan is not an allegory (a simple one-to-one code) so much as a **supposal**: *suppose* Christ were to enter a talking-animal world, what might that look like?

Aslan appears in every book of the series, always central to the resolution — though in *The Voyage of the Dawn Treader* and *The Silver Chair*, he is present mostly through signs, guiding from a distance.

## The Magician's Nephew: Creation and the Fall

*The Magician's Nephew* (published sixth but set first in Narnia's history) depicts the **creation of Narnia** — Aslan singing the world into existence in one of the most beautiful passages in all of fantasy literature. It also depicts the introduction of evil into Narnia: Digory's wicked Uncle Andrew and the witch Jadis (who will become the White Witch) are brought into the newly made world before it is ready.

The story of Digory's temptation — standing before a tree bearing an apple of immortality, with the witch urging him to take it for himself — directly parallels the Garden of Eden. Digory resists the temptation, and Aslan honors his obedience.

## The Last Battle: The End of Narnia

*The Last Battle* — which won the Carnegie Medal as the best British children's book of 1956 — depicts the end of Narnia's history in apocalyptic terms deeply reminiscent of the Book of Revelation. Narnia falls to deception and apostasy; the final battle is lost. But then Aslan calls all creatures to pass through a doorway, where they discover that the Narnia they loved was only the "Shadowlands" — the real Narnia, deeper and more vivid and eternal, lies beyond.

Lewis's vision of the afterlife is eloquent and moving:

:::quote C.S. Lewis, *The Last Battle*
"'I have come home at last! This is my real country! I belong here. This is the land I have been looking for all my life, though I never knew it till now.'"
:::

The idea that earthly beauty and joy are "shadowlands" pointing to a fuller reality is central to Lewis's apologetic project — the argument from *Sehnsucht* (longing), which he develops more formally in *Mere Christianity* and *The Weight of Glory*.

## Why Lewis Wrote for Children

Lewis believed that the best children's literature treats children as genuine persons with real minds and real spiritual needs. He also had a deeper purpose: he wanted to present Christian truth in a form that bypassed the psychological barriers many modern people had erected against it. By presenting Christ's story in the form of Aslan's story in Narnia — at an imaginative distance, stripped of ecclesiastical associations — Lewis hoped to make the Gospel feel fresh and wondrous again.

He once wrote that he wanted "to steal past the watchful dragons" of familiarity and prejudice that prevented many from receiving the Gospel with childlike openness.

## Educational Value and Recommendations

*The Chronicles of Narnia* are excellent starting points for:
- **Young readers** encountering Christian ideas for the first time in story form
- **Older students** exploring the relationship between imagination, myth, and truth
- **Adults** seeking accessible Lewis before tackling *Mere Christianity* or *The Screwtape Letters*

Read in conjunction with Lewis's theological essays — particularly *On Three Ways of Writing for Children* and *Sometimes Fairy Stories May Say Best What's to Be Said* — the Chronicles reveal the careful pastoral and apologetic intention behind every page.

